answers.body_markdown:
You don&#39;t actually connect &quot;by role.&quot; You connect with a username and a password. 

Roles are how users are organized *on the broker*. You can have one or more users in a given role and then permissions are granted to that role as a whole. This makes it easier to organize users and configure security.

Keep in mind that the security configuration for messaging users (e.g. those using JMS) is separate from management users (e.g. those using JMX). The former is done via `security-settings` in `broker.xml` and the latter is done via `authorisation` in `management.xml`.

In your case, you can supply credentials for the JMX connection like so:
```java
         HashMap env = new HashMap();
         String[] creds = {&quot;myUser&quot;, &quot;myPassword&quot;};
         env.put(JMXConnector.CREDENTIALS, creds);

         JMXConnector connector = JMXConnectorFactory.connect(new JMXServiceURL(BuildGet.JMX_URL), env);
```
It&#39;s important to note that your `connectBroker` method is **leaking** a JMS connection every time it is invoked. This is because you create a JMS connection, but you don&#39;t close it or return it from the method. I recommend removing the JMS connection from that method entirely as it servers no real purpose.

